{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9dee872e-9e3b-4d09-8ea1-c33a62937f53","content":"Here's the evaluation performance analysis for `EvalHeavy.csproj`:\n\n## Issues Found\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files during evaluation blocks the MSBuild evaluation phase. This runs on **every** evaluation (IDE open, build, restore). Move file reading to a target with `Inputs/Outputs` so it only runs at execution time.\n\n### 2. Expensive Glob Pattern (Medium Impact)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nA recursive `**\\*.*` glob walks the entire directory tree during evaluation. If the tree grows (e.g., `node_modules`, large artifact folders), this becomes very slow. Narrow the glob to specific extensions or directories, or add large folders to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n### 3. Chained Import Depth (Low Impact)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels of chained imports. This is minor here but becomes a problem at scale (>20 levels). Each import adds evaluation overhead.\n\n---\n\n**Recommendation priority:** Fix the `File::ReadAllText` call first — it's synchronous disk I/O during evaluation and the biggest offender. Then tighten the glob pattern.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5e5199c0-4c85-463a-b383-ad1ec7233e4f","outputTokens":354,"requestId":"0410:26CE6:693BC:7CEC5:69F2AE44"},"id":"60c266f9-a766-4953-b98d-24e05a170b0e","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:20:14.229Z","parentId":"c1eb0564-eb41-4494-8644-2b1218059b79"}
